## ArtCade architecture guardrails

These rules are project-specific and outrank generic web-app guidance.

**Authoritative contract (full paletti):**
[`.cursor/rules/artcade-architecture-authority.mdc`](artcade-architecture-authority.mdc) — always apply. The bullets below are the operational subset used in reviews; when they conflict with convenience, the authority rule wins.

### ProjectDocument authority

- `ProjectDocument` / `ProjectDoc` is the single source of truth for persisted authoring data: scenes, objects, assets, prefab/object types, components, Logic Board data, dialogs, script attachments, and project settings.
- UI components may display snapshots, dispatch commands/intents, and receive updated snapshots. They must not directly mutate durable entities, scenes, assets, prefab/object types, or rulesheets.
- Every persistent authoring change must pass through the command/intent path that handles validation, dirty state, revision, and undo/redo.
- It is forbidden to maintain two equivalent mutable states by manual synchronization. If two representations exist, one must be derived deterministically from the other.
- Dirty is `revision != savedRevision` (and script `bufferRevision != savedBufferRevision`) — not a hand-kept boolean second authority.

### Editor state vs game state

- `ProjectDocument` / `ProjectDoc`: saved authoring data.
- `EditorWorkspaceState`: temporary editor state such as selection, zoom, visible grid, rulers, panel layout, focus mode, active tool, snap, and open tabs.
- `EditorUiState` (layout prefs): splitters, console, filters — not project undo.
- `PlaySession`: runtime state during play/test; materializes once; lost on Stop; authoring commands blocked while playing.
- `PlaySession` must never dirty or mutate `ProjectDocument` unless the user performs an explicit authoring command.
- UI-only toggles, zoom, selection, visible grid/rulers, panel state, and focus mode must not produce undo/redo entries or dirty the project.

### Single voice (no dual paths)

**One control surface → one authority → one write path.** Applies to Qt QML, C++ bridge, and `artcade_editor_core`.

- Toolbar buttons, shortcuts, and Scene View gestures that mean the same action must call the **same** `EditorSession` / coordinator API — never a parallel QML-local copy of tool/snap/selection that is manually synced.
- Workspace fields (`activeTool`, `snapEnabled`, selection, active layer) live in **one** place (`EditorSession` / coordinator workspace). Views bind and display; they do not own a second mutable mirror.
- Ephemeral gesture state (drag preview, marquee in progress) may live on the Scene View surface, but the **result** (select, commit position) always goes through the session intent path.
- Forbidden: two buttons or two code paths that both mutate the same authoring/workspace fact through different stacks.

### Undo/redo and dirty state

- Only authoring commands that persistently change `ProjectDocument` create undo/redo history, dirty flags, and project revisions.
- Script buffer history is separate; route Undo/Redo by focus (code editor vs rest).
- Reducers or services must guard no-op edits so click/drag, selection churn, and replayed runtime echoes do not mark the project dirty.
- A change that mutates saved project data without undo/redo coverage is a SHOULD-FIX; if it can cause data loss or silent persistence drift, it is a BLOCKER.

### Stable identity

- Objects, scenes, assets, prefab/object types, components, dialogs, Logic Board rulesheets, layers, and generated outputs must use stable IDs internally.
- Names are display labels only. Paths are location only. Using a name or path as an internal key is a SHOULD-FIX.
- Generated objects/prefabs must not create duplicate names in the same authoring scope. Block the operation or require/derive an explicit unique name.

### Object Type, instances, layers

- Object Type owns shared defaults; EntityInstance owns sparse overrides; one canonical resolver for Inspector, Scene View, validator, Play, and export.
- `SceneDef.layers` is the only visual order authority; instances reference `layerId`. No parallel LayerManager as a second authority.

### Logic Board & Script

- Logic Board is type-owned (`objectTypes[].logicBoard`), descriptor-driven, compiled via C++ `compileProjectLogic` into **LogicRuntime** at Play/load; generated Logic Lua must not overwrite `scripts/main.lua` (My Script).
- Script attachments remain separate programs on the same gameplay host; adapters stay thin.
- Behavior scripts are type-owned; project scripts are global ordered; Lua source lives on disk under the project root (relative paths only).
- Logic and Script share one gameplay host API but remain separate programs. Editor Play and export must share semantics (feature DoD is end-to-end).
- No automatic hot-reload MVP; deferred destroy; Lua sandbox (no Raylib/OS/FS/ProjectDocument).

### Central validation and current-format contracts

- Every document mutation must pass centralized schema/validator logic. The UI is not the validity authority.
- Import, paste, AI generation, drag/drop, manual edit, and file load must use the same validation path.
- Every saved `ProjectDocument` must carry a schema/version marker.
- Any breaking saved-format change requires an explicit version bump plus current-format fixture/round-trip test. Do not retain or convert older formats; reject them with a clear error.

### Asset registry

- Assets must be referenced through registry-backed `AssetRef` / stable asset IDs, not scattered raw paths.
- Import, move, rename, and delete must update the asset registry atomically.
- Before deleting an asset, check dependencies from scenes, object types, tilemaps, dialogs, Logic Board actions, and generated/runtime payloads.
- Generated SFX recipes are authoring-only; runtime consumes AudioAssetDefs only.

### Scene surface & Raylib boundary

- Raylib is a backend, not the engine architecture. The Qt Scene View hosts presentation and the runtime/Raylib surface owns pixels.
- Prefer a long-lived connected canvas (pin-on-body binder). Detach/reparent churn that breaks presentation is a defect, not an acceptable pattern.
- One Scene View camera for render, pick, drag, snap, overlay, and grid.

### Runtime hot-path performance

- In runtime/play hot paths, avoid unnecessary per-frame allocations, clones, JSON serialization, and container churn.
- Any allocation in the game loop must be intentional, measured or bounded, and justified by the surrounding code.
- Qt editor code may allocate normally where it is not on a per-frame or compile-on-keystroke path; review performance in context, not as a blanket ban.

